-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: AccessKenya, Kenya Power, Naiade, Sun Resorts
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k   a n d   K a m l e s h   B h u c k o r y
-- 2010-12-23T15:00:14Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-23/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-accesskenya-kenya-power-naiade-sun.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  advanced
for a second day, rising 0.8 percent to 1,928.46 by the 1:30
p.m. close in Port Louis.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index  climbed for the third day in four,
adding 0.2 percent to close at 77.41 by 3 p.m. in Nairobi. The
 Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  rose for a second day,
up 0.4 percent to 24,700.15 by 2:30 p.m. in Lagos, according to
data compiled by Bloomberg. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index 
snapped five days of gains, dropping 0.1 percent to 861.13 by
4:22 p.m. in Windhoek while the  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share
Index  rose 0.2 percent to 7,191.68 by the 1 p.m. close in Accra,
the first increase in four days.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  AccessKenya Group Ltd.  (ACCESS KN), the country’s only
publicly traded Internet company, snapped the longest falling
streak since March 2009, gaining 5 cents, or 0.4 percent, to 13
shillings on speculation investors viewed a 19 percent drop in
the period as overdone, Aly-Khan Satchu, a Nairobi-based
independent stock-market analyst, said in a phone interview.  Kenya Power & Lighting Ltd.  (KPLL KN), the East African
nation’s sole power distributor, rose for the first time in
eight trading days, adding 25 cents, or 1.2 percent, to 22
shillings. Kenya’s economy grew 6.1 percent in the third quarter
compared with 0.5 percent a year earlier, the Kenya National
Bureau of Statistics said in a Dec. 21 report. In that period,
there was “reliable supply of electricity and resilient domestic
demand,” it said.  “The economy is growing and this has pushed up demand for
power,” Aly-Khan Satchu, a Nairobi-based independent stock-
market analyst, said in a phone interview today.  Naiade Resorts Ltd.  (NRL MP), a Mauritian hotel operator,
climbed the most since Oct. 5, surging 2.6 rupees, or 11
percent, to 25.5 rupees. Chief Executive Officer  Paul Jones  told
l’Express newspaper he expects this year’s performance to
significantly improve, with the copmany poised to report
positive results for the quarter through December.  Sun Resorts Ltd.  (SUN MP), Mauritius’s second-biggest hotel
operator by market value, rallied for a second day, rising 1
rupee, or 1.9 percent, to 54 rupees. MCB Stockbrokers Ltd.
raised its net profit forecast for the year through December to
209 million rupees ($6.7 million) from 144 million rupees, Port
Louis-based analyst  Vanessa Lai Min  wrote in an e-mailed report
sent today. Lai Min set a price estimate of 60 rupees a share by
May 2011 for Sun.  To contact the reporters on this story:
